description.narrative:
Reprogrammed funds to mitigate the impact of COVID-19 There are approximately 370 million indigenous peoples globally. Of that figure, Asia is a home to 260 million indigenous peoples. Two thousand distinct civilizations and languages are found in the region, making Asia the ethnically most diverse continent in the world. Mostly living in a remote and inaccessible areas, indigenous peoples’ lives are profoundly connected to land, natural resources and local livelihoods. For centuries, indigenous peoples have been discriminated, exploited and oppressed by the dominant groups in control of the state. Discrimination come in various forms such as withholding citizenship or rights, displacement, exploitation of traditional knowledge, denial of access to legal avenues and protection, exclusion from welfare and neglected by civil society. The rapid economic development in Asia has increased the overall living standard of its populations out of poverty. However, such advancement has achieved at the expense of the indigenous peoples since they remain the most marginalized and vulnerable group of the society and have higher poverty rates than national average.
Internationally, there are legal frameworks or instruments which recognize the rights of indigenous peoples and the need to protect their rights. UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIP), adopted in 2007, establishes a universal framework of minimum standards for the survival, dignity and well-being of the indigenous peoples which elaborates on existing human rights standards and fundamental freedoms as they apply to the specific situation of indigenous peoples. The ILO Convention 169 “Concerning Indigenous and Tribal Peoples in Independent Countries” highlights the indigenous peoples' right to land, territories, resources, collective rights to self-determination and right to free, prior and informed consent. Nevertheless, the implementation of legal frameworks is not well pursued in the reality since the rights of indigenous people are often disregarded and violated. In Asia, the recognition of indigenous peoples and their rights at a country level varies considerably subject to the decision-makers’ interpretation and judgement, which often is politically driven and not transparent. Asia has projected regressive development in human rights in recent years which can be seen from the infringement of the rule of law, frequent cases of impunity, shrinking of democratic and civic space, arbitrary arrest of opposition and public dissident and threatening actions towards human rights activists. The situation appears to be direr for indigenous peoples given land grabbing continues to rise and so does the loss of lives of indigenous rights activists and community members. Indigenous peoples are at the highest risks of violence and threats particularly the Environmental Human Rights Defenders (EHRDs). Further than the above challenges, Asian key structural development issues including weak legal mechanism, inadequate social safeguard and little awareness concerning indigenous peoples also significantly impede the opportunities for indigenous communities in consolidating their agenda for collective actions and transformative changes. The proposed intervention “Promoting Indigenous Peoples’ Rights in Asia for a Future of Peace, Justice and Equality, submitted by Asia Indigenous Peoples Pact (AIPP) seeks to increase the recognition and protection of indigenous peoples rights in Asia through the implementation of its Strategic Plan which has an overall objective to strengthen the solidarity, cooperation and capacities of indigenous peoples in Asia to promote and defend their rights, cultures and identities, and their sustainable resource management systems and self-determined development. The proposed intervention is 3 years-duration from January 2019 to December 2021. The contribution from Sweden will cover the proportional shortfall under this strategic plan where the cost of activities cannot be covered by the existing agreement with other donors since the supports are activities specific. To achieve the overarching objective of the strategic plan, the activities are planned and channel through five result areas as follow.
Result Area 1: Indigenous peoples in Asia are empowered to promote, claim and defend legal recognition of their identities and collective and individual human rights including the right to self-determination.
Result Area 2: Indigenous movements in Asia are strengthened by building broad solidarity and cooperation among indigenous peoples as well as with other social movements towards achieving equality, peace, democracy and justice;
Result Area 3: The protection of the integrity of the natural environment is promoted and the sustainable resource management systems of indigenous peoples including their skills and traditional knowledge for food security, livelihood and protection of biodiversity is enhanced by having full control over their lands, territories and their resources;
Result Area 4: Full and effective participation of indigenous women, and youth as well as vulnerable people, like indigenous persons with disabilities (IPwD) and elderly etc., and their capacities to promote and protect their rights;
Result Area 5: AIPP’s governance, the secretariat and member organisations are strengthened.
The implementation of AIPP current strategic plan has integrated the four-pronged approaches consisting of capacity building, advocacy and lobbying, organizational strengthening and research and communication into all its programme activities. The activities are delivered by AIPP 6 programme units which are Human Rights, Campaign and Policy Advocacy Programme, Environment Programme, Indigenous Women Programme, regional capacity building programme, communication development programme and organizational strengthening and movement building. Importantly, the implementation of this strategic plan also attempts to rectify the critical gap at country and sub-regional level in their organizational planning which is the key observation from AIPP evaluation in 2016. To bridge the gap, AIPP has adopted systematic bottom-up process in its operation under this strategic plan to conduct situation assessment, thematic mapping, prioritization and planning. Robust communication and consultation with the member organisations and networks are key for AIPP to successfully pursue the bottom-up consultative approach. It is anticipated that such practice will help establishing regular review mechanism and coordination among member organizations which will enable AIPP to overcome existing barriers and weaknesses regarding strengthening solidarity and unity, and lack of common agenda and coherence in strategy in their advocacy activities at the country-level. This can also contribute to the consolidation and unification of the indigenous communities which currently remain fragmented and have not been able to effectively build their movements.
